title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  R^{*}]]></fr:tex> be a nonzero element. Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is prime. Then for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a,d\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} ad]]></fr:tex> we have
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\hbox {either }p\mathrel {\bigm |} a\hbox { or }p\mathrel {\bigm |} d,]]></fr:tex>
by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-001T.xml"
addr="ra-001T"
title="Prime element">definition of prime</fr:link>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Now, by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-001U.xml"
addr="ra-001U"
title="Irreducible element">definition of irreducible</fr:link>, suppose we had some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d\in  R]]></fr:tex>
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[d\mathrel {\bigm |} p.]]></fr:tex>
We will show that either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d=pu]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d=u]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-000I.xml"
addr="ra-000I"
title="Unit">unit</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  R]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d\mathrel {\bigm |} p]]></fr:tex>, this means there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p=ad]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is prime and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} p]]></fr:tex> (i.e., <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} ad]]></fr:tex>), this means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} a]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} d]]></fr:tex>. Then we argue by cases.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Case 1:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} a]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a=pb]]></fr:tex>. But then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p=ad=(pb)d]]></fr:tex>, using distributivity and subtraction gives us
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[(1-bd)p=0.]]></fr:tex>
Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[bd=1]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\neq 0]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> is a unit, since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is an integral domain. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is irreducible by definition.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Case 2:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} d]]></fr:tex>. The argument is similar to case 1.</fr:p><html:span
